​1. Introduction
​The Portfolio of Evidence (PoE) for this Web Development module serves as a rigorous, hands-on capstone project designed to test our proficiency in architecting and implementing dynamic, database-driven web systems. My understanding of this PoE is that it evaluates our readiness to build production-ready applications without the luxury of pre-built framework modernizations like Laravel or jQuery. We were required to write pure server-side PHP, native HTML/CSS layouts, and raw SQL queries to manage complex client-server interactions.
​Our group addressed the sustainable, community-driven e-commerce market in South Africa by developing PASTIMES—a highly secure, second-hand clothing retail exchange application. The primary engineering challenge of this PoE lay in orchestrating three separate user interfaces (Buyer, Seller, and Admin dashboards) that interface seamlessly with a single, highly relational MySQL database structure. Ultimately, the assignment forced us to master core software architecture concepts such as native state preservation, secure role-based session management, and asynchronous data transfer, bridging the gap between theoretical computing logic and functional web development.
